Data Visualization (STAT 302)

Overview

The goal of this lab is to play around with the theme options in ggplot2.

Datasets

Weâll be using the cdc.txt and NU_admission_data.csv datasets.

Code 
# load package(s)
library(tidyverse)
library(patchwork)
library(showtext)

# read in the cdc dataset
cdc <- read_delim(file = "data/cdc.txt", delim = "|") %>%
  mutate(
    genhlth = factor(
      genhlth,
      levels = c("excellent", "very good", "good", "fair", "poor"),
      labels = c("Excellent", "Very Good", "Good", "Fair", "Poor")
      )
    )

# read in NU admission data
nu_data <- read.csv("data/NU_admission_data.csv") %>%
  janitor::clean_names()

# set seed
set.seed(2468)

# selecting a random subset of size 100
cdc_small <- cdc %>% 
  slice_sample(n = 100)

Exercise 1

Use the cdc_small dataset to explore several pre-set ggthemes. The code below constructs the familiar scatterplot of weight by height and stores it in plot_01. Display plot_01 to observe the default theme. Explore/apply, and display at least 7 other pre-set themes from the ggplot2 or ggthemes package. Donât worry about making adjustments to the figures under the new themes. Just get a sense of what the themes are doing to the original figure plot_01.

There should be at least 8 plots for this task, plot_01 is pictured below. Use patchwork or cowplot in combination with R yaml chunk options fig-height and fig-width (out-width and fig-align may be useful as well) to setup the 8 plots together in a user friendly arrangement.


Code 
# plot
plot_01 <- ggplot(
  data = cdc_small,
  aes(x = height, y = weight)
) +
  geom_point(size = 3, aes(shape = genhlth, color = genhlth)) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "Weight in Pounds",
    limits = c(100, 275),
    breaks = seq(100, 275, 25),
    trans = "log10",
    labels = scales::label_number(
      accuracy = 1,
      suffix = " lbs"
    )
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "Height in Inches",
    limits = c(60, 80),
    breaks = seq(60, 80, 5),
    labels = scales::label_number(accuracy = 1, suffix = " in")
  ) +
  scale_shape_manual(
    name = "Health?",
    labels = c(
      "Excellent", "Very Good",
      "Good", "Fair", "Poor"
    ),
    values = c(17, 19, 15, 9, 4)
  ) +
  scale_color_brewer(
    name = "Health?",
    labels = c(
      "Excellent", "Very Good",
      "Good", "Fair", "Poor"
    ),
    palette = "Set1"
  ) +
  theme(
    legend.position = c(1, 0),
    legend.justification = c(1, 0)
  ) +
  labs(title = "CDC BRFSS: Weight by Height")

# plot_01 in 7 different themes
plot_02 <- plot_01 + theme_void()
plot_03 <- plot_01 + ggthemes::theme_solarized()
plot_04 <- plot_01 + theme_light()
plot_05 <- plot_01 + theme_bw()
plot_06 <- plot_01 + theme_dark()
plot_07 <- plot_01 + theme_minimal()
plot_08 <- plot_01 + theme_classic()

# display plots

(plot_01 + plot_02 + plot_03 + plot_04) / (plot_05 + plot_06 + plot_07 + plot_08)

Important

Which theme or themes do you particularly like? Why?

I like the more minimalist themes such as theme_void() and theme_classic() more because they present a cleaner image of the graph. Since the graph is already loud with many shapes and colors, it is best to try to keep further annotations and details to a minimum, which can be accomplished with the minimalist themes.

Exercise 2

Using plot_01 from Exercise 1 and the theme() function, attempt to construct the ugliest plot possible (example pictured below). Be creative! It should NOT look exactly like the example. Since the goal is to understand a variety of adjustments, you should use a minimum of 10 different manual adjustments within theme().

Code 
ggplot(
  data = cdc_small,
  aes(x = height, y = weight)
) +
  geom_point(size = 3, aes(shape = genhlth, color = genhlth)) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "Weight in Pounds",
    limits = c(100, 275),
    breaks = seq(100, 275, 25),
    trans = "log10",
    labels = scales::label_number(
      accuracy = 1,
      suffix = " lbs"
    )
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "Height in Inches",
    limits = c(60, 80),
    breaks = seq(60, 80, 5),
    labels = scales::label_number(accuracy = 1, suffix = " in")
  ) +
  scale_shape_manual(
    name = "Health?",
    labels = c(
      "Excellent", "Very Good",
      "Good", "Fair", "Poor"
    ),
    values = c(17, 19, 15, 9, 4)
  ) +
  scale_color_brewer(
    name = "Health?",
    labels = c(
      "Excellent", "Very Good",
      "Good", "Fair", "Poor"
    ),
    palette = "Set1"
  ) +
  theme(
    legend.position = c(1, 0),
    legend.justification = c(1, 0),
  
    legend.box.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = "red"),
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = "pink"),
    legend.direction = "horizontal",
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "green"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(color = "blue"),
    axis.title.y = element_text(color = "yellow"),
    axis.ticks = element_line(color = "magenta"),
    panel.grid = element_line(linetype = "twodash"),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "black"),
    title = element_text(color = "turquoise", size = 25),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 3)
  ) +
  labs(title = "CDC BRFSS: Weight by Height")

Exercise 3

We will be making use of your code from Exercise 3 from L07 Layers. Using the NU_admission_data.csv you created two separate plots derived from the single plot depicted in undergraduate-admissions-statistics.pdf. Style these plots so they follow a âNorthwesternâ theme. You are welcome to display the plots separately OR design a layout that displays both together (likely one stacked above the other).

Additional requirement:

Use a free non-standard font from google for the title. Pick one that looks similar to a Northwestern font.

Code 
# BARPLOT
bar_data <- nu_data %>%
  filter(year > 1999) %>% 
  select(-contains("_rate")) %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = -year,
    names_to = "category",
    values_to = "count"
  ) 

#bar chart labels dataset
bar_label_data <- bar_data %>% 
  mutate(col_label = prettyNum(count, big.mark = ","))

#barplot
barplot <- ggplot(bar_data, aes(x = year, y = count)) +
  geom_col(
    aes(fill = category), 
    position = "identity",
    width = 0.6
    ) +
  geom_text(
    data = bar_label_data,
    aes(label = col_label),
    color = "white",
    size = 2,
    vjust = 1,
    nudge_y = -200
    ) +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "Entering Year",
    breaks = 2000:2020,
    expand = c(0, 0.25)
    ) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "Appllications",
    breaks = seq(0, 50000, 5000),
    labels = scales::label_comma(),
    limits = c(0, 45000),
    expand = c(0, 0)
    ) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    name = NULL,
    limits = c("applications", "admitted_students", "matriculants"),
    labels = c("Applicants   ", "Admitted students   ", "Matriculants"),
    values = c("#B6ACD1", "#836EAA", "#4E2A84")
    ) 

#LINE PLOT

#line plot dataset
line_data <- nu_data %>% 
  filter(year > 1999) %>% 
  select(year, admission_rate, yield_rate) %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = -year, 
    names_to = "type", 
    values_to = "rate")

#line plot labels dataset
line_label_data <- line_data %>% 
  mutate(rate_labels = str_c(rate, "%"),
         label_y = case_when(
           type == "admission_rate" ~ rate - 2,
           type == "yield_rate" ~ rate + 2
           )
         ) 

#lineplot
lineplot <- ggplot(line_data, aes(x = year, y = rate)) +
  geom_line(
    aes(color = type)
    ) +
  geom_point(
    mapping = aes(shape = type, fill = type),
    color = "white"
    ) +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_x_continuous(
    name = "Entering Year",
    breaks = 2000:2020,
    expand = c(0, 0.35)
    ) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    name = "Rate",
    labels = scales::label_percent(scale = 1),
    limits = c(0, 60),
    breaks = seq(0, 60, 10),
    expand = c(0,0)
    ) +
  scale_shape_manual(
    name = NULL, 
    values = c(21, 24),
    labels = c("Admission rate", "Yield rate"),
    ) +
  scale_color_manual(
    name = NULL, 
    labels = c("Admission rate", "Yield rate"),
    values = c("#4E2A84", "#836EAA")
    ) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    name = NULL,
    labels = c("Admission rate", "Yield rate"),
    values = c("#4E2A84", "#836EAA")
    ) +
  geom_text(
    data = line_label_data,
    aes(y = label_y, label = rate_labels),
    size = 3
    )
